<DOC><DOCNO> AP890516-0138 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1625EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-ExtortionIndictment     05-16 0279</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Extortion Indictment,250</SECOND><HEAD>Virginian Accused of Trying to Extort $2 Million from Coca-Cola Co.</HEAD><DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal grand jury on Tuesday indicteda Virginia man on charges that he tried to extort $2 million fromthe Coca-Cola Co. and two of its top officials by threatening topoison their products.   The 14-count indictment charged Lester L. Hummer, about 47, withextortion, interstate travel in aid of a racketeering enterprise,attempting to tamper with consumer products and mailing threateningcommunications.   Hummer, of Berryville, Va., allegedly sent several extortionletters to Coca-Cola President and Chief Operating Officer DonaldR. Keough and Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Roberto C.Goizueta between Feb. 22 and April 16, when he was arrested.   Hummer was arrested at a drop site near Washington-DullesInternational Airport where he was to be paid. He has been heldwithout bond since his arrest. Arraignment is scheduled Mondaybefore U.S. District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr.   U.S. Attorney Henry Hudson said there was no evidence thatHummer or anyone else actually tampered with any products.   ``Due to the cooperation of the Coca-Cola Co. and theextraordinary investigative skills of the Federal Bureau ofInvestigation, I am convinced that we have arrested the onlyindividual who was involved in these extortion attempts and havedone so prior to his carrying out any of the threats he has made inthis matter,'' Hudson said in a statement.   Hummer faces a maximum prison term of 145 years and a fine of$3.5 million if convicted on all counts.   Coca-Cola spokesman Randy Donaldson declined to comment on thecase, other than to say the company had cooperated fully withauthorities.</TEXT></DOC>